---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { webPageSchema, breadcrumbSchema } from '../lib/schema';

const structuredData = [
  webPageSchema({
    name: 'What Is Menopause? A Guide for Indian Women | The Second Spring',
    description: 'Menopause is a single point in time — not a phase, not a disease. Here is what it means, what changes, and what life looks like on the other side.',
    url: '/menopause',
  }),
  breadcrumbSchema([
    { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
    { name: 'Menopause', url: '/menopause' },
  ]),
];
---

<Layout
  title="What Is Menopause? A Guide for Indian Women | The Second Spring"
  description="Menopause is a single point in time — not a phase, not a disease. Here is what it means, what changes, and what life looks like on the other side."
  structuredData={structuredData}
>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="ig-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ig-hero-inner">
        <div class="ig-eyebrow">🌿 Guide</div>
        <h1>What Is Menopause?</h1>
        <p>Menopause is not the beginning of decline — it is a transition point. Here is what it actually means for your body, your health, and your life.</p>
        <div class="ig-share-row">
          <span class="ig-share-label">Share this guide</span>
          <a href="https://wa.me/?text=What is menopause — explained for Indian women: https://thesecondspring.org/menopause" target="_blank" class="ig-share-btn ig-wa">WhatsApp</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 01 — DEFINITION -->
  <section class="ig-section bg-white">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ig-card ig-card--full">
        <div class="ig-card-label">01 / What Menopause Actually Is</div>
        <h2 class="ig-card-title">Menopause is <em>one day</em> — everything before it is perimenopause</h2>

        <div class="def-intro">
          <p>The word "menopause" is used loosely to describe an entire life phase — but medically, it is a single specific point in time:</p>
        </div>

        <div class="def-blocks">
          <div class="def-block def-block--peri">
            <div class="def-block-icon">🌊</div>
            <div class="def-block-label">Perimenopause</div>
            <div class="def-block-desc">The transition phase before menopause. Hormones fluctuate erratically. Symptoms begin. Periods become irregular. Can last 4–10 years. <a href="/perimenopause-explained" class="def-link">Learn more →</a></div>
          </div>
          <div class="def-arrow">→</div>
          <div class="def-block def-block--meno">
            <div class="def-block-icon">📅</div>
            <div class="def-block-label">Menopause</div>
            <div class="def-block-desc"><strong>12 consecutive months without a period.</strong> That specific date — one year after your last period — is menopause. A single point, not a phase.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="def-arrow">→</div>
          <div class="def-block def-block--post">
            <div class="def-block-icon">🌅</div>
            <div class="def-block-label">Postmenopause</div>
            <div class="def-block-desc">Every day after that date. Hormones settle at a lower, steadier level. Many women feel more stable than they did during the erratic perimenopause years.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-wrap" style="margin-top:2.5rem;">
          <div class="tl-item">
            <div class="tl-dot tl-dot--green"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
              <div class="tl-age">Late 30s – mid 40s (often earlier in India)</div>
              <div class="tl-label">Perimenopause begins</div>
              <div class="tl-desc">Hormones begin to fluctuate. Irregular periods, symptoms, sleepless nights. You are still ovulating — and still can get pregnant.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-line"></div>
          <div class="tl-item tl-item--now">
            <div class="tl-dot tl-dot--peach tl-dot--pulse"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
              <div class="tl-age">India avg: 46–47 · Western avg: ~51</div>
              <div class="tl-label tl-label--highlight">Menopause (single point)</div>
              <div class="tl-desc">12 months after your last period. You only know you have reached it <em>retrospectively</em> — after 12 months have passed. Confirmed in hindsight, not in the moment.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-line"></div>
          <div class="tl-item">
            <div class="tl-dot tl-dot--light"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
              <div class="tl-age">50s, 60s, 70s and beyond</div>
              <div class="tl-label">Postmenopause</div>
              <div class="tl-desc">Periods have stopped permanently. Hormones are low but stable. This phase can last 30–40 years — long-term health protection matters.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="ig-callout ig-callout--peach">
          <span class="ig-callout-icon">💡</span>
          <span><strong>Menopause is not diagnosed — it is confirmed retrospectively.</strong> You only know you have reached it after 12 months without a period. During those 12 months, you are still in perimenopause, still at risk of pregnancy, and still eligible for the same treatments.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="ig-callout" style="margin-top:1rem;">
          <span class="ig-callout-icon">🇮🇳</span>
          <span>Indian women reach menopause at an average age of <strong>46–47</strong> — 4–5 years earlier than Western women, who average around 51. This means a longer postmenopausal life, which makes long-term health protection even more important.</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 02 — WHAT CHANGES POSTMENOPAUSE -->
  <section class="ig-section bg-cream">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ig-card-label center">02 / What Changes After Menopause</div>
      <h2 class="ig-section-title center">What actually changes when you reach menopause</h2>
      <p class="ig-section-sub center">Two things happen at once — some things improve, and some things need more deliberate attention over the long term.</p>

      <div class="changes-grid">
        <div class="changes-col changes-col--improves">
          <div class="changes-head">
            <div class="changes-head-icon">✨</div>
            <div class="changes-head-text">What often <strong>improves</strong></div>
          </div>
          <ul class="changes-list">
            <li>Erratic mood swings ease as hormones stop surging and crashing</li>
            <li>Irregular, unpredictable periods — they stop entirely</li>
            <li>Breast tenderness that was cycle-related</li>
            <li>The feeling of hormonal chaos and unpredictability</li>
            <li>For many women, hot flashes and night sweats gradually reduce in the years after menopause</li>
            <li>A sense of stability and knowing where you are in your cycle — because cycles have ended</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="changes-note">
            Many women find postmenopause more stable than the rollercoaster years of perimenopause — once symptoms are managed.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="changes-col changes-col--attention">
          <div class="changes-head">
            <div class="changes-head-icon">🔍</div>
            <div class="changes-head-text">What needs <strong>long-term attention</strong></div>
          </div>
          <ul class="changes-list changes-list--attention">
            <li>
              <strong>🦴 Bone density</strong> — oestrogen's decline accelerates bone loss significantly after menopause. Indian women have lower baseline bone density than Western women, making osteoporosis risk substantial and under-diagnosed.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>❤️ Cardiovascular health</strong> — oestrogen was protective for your heart and blood vessels. Postmenopause, cardiovascular disease risk rises. It is the leading cause of death in postmenopausal women.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>💧 Vaginal and urinary health (GSM)</strong> — genitourinary syndrome of menopause causes dryness, discomfort, and recurrent UTIs. Unlike hot flashes, GSM tends to worsen over time if left untreated.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>⚖️ Metabolic changes</strong> — insulin resistance, weight gain, and blood sugar changes established during perimenopause continue into postmenopause.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="ig-callout" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <span class="ig-callout-icon">🪟</span>
        <span><strong>The window of opportunity:</strong> starting HRT during perimenopause or within 10 years of reaching menopause has the greatest protective effect on bones and heart — and emerging evidence suggests possible cognitive benefit, though this is still being studied. The earlier you start, the more protective benefit you receive — waiting until symptoms become severe means missing this window.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 03 — SYMPTOMS: WHAT CONTINUES VS WHAT EASES -->
  <section class="ig-section bg-white">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ig-card-label center">03 / Symptoms Over Time</div>
      <h2 class="ig-section-title center">Which symptoms ease after menopause — and which persist</h2>
      <p class="ig-section-sub center">Reaching menopause does not mean symptoms switch off. But the picture changes — and much of it responds well to treatment.</p>

      <div class="symptoms-grid">
        <div class="symptom-col symptom-col--eases">
          <div class="symptom-col-badge symptom-col-badge--eases">Often eases postmenopause</div>
          <div class="symptom-items">
            <div class="symptom-item">
              <div class="symptom-icon">🌊</div>
              <div class="symptom-text">
                <div class="symptom-name">Erratic mood swings</div>
                <div class="symptom-reason">Hormones stabilise at a lower level — the surges and crashes that drove rapid mood shifts reduce</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="symptom-item">
              <div class="symptom-icon">📅</div>
              <div class="symptom-text">
                <div class="symptom-name">Irregular periods</div>
                <div class="symptom-reason">Periods stop entirely — no more guessing, flooding, or unpredictable cycles</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="symptom-item">
              <div class="symptom-icon">🤲</div>
              <div class="symptom-text">
                <div class="symptom-name">Breast tenderness</div>
                <div class="symptom-reason">Cycle-linked breast pain eases when cycles end</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="symptom-item">
              <div class="symptom-icon">🌡️</div>
              <div class="symptom-text">
                <div class="symptom-name">Hot flashes (for many)</div>
                <div class="symptom-reason">Hot flashes are most intense in late perimenopause — many (not all) women find they gradually reduce in the years after menopause</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="symptom-col symptom-col--persists">
          <div class="symptom-col-badge symptom-col-badge--persists">Often persists or worsens without treatment</div>
          <div class="symptom-items">
            <div class="symptom-item">
              <div class="symptom-icon">💧</div>
              <div class="symptom-text">
                <div class="symptom-name">Vaginal dryness &amp; urinary symptoms</div>
                <div class="symptom-reason">GSM is progressive — unlike hot flashes, it worsens over time if not treated. Vaginal oestrogen is safe, effective, and not widely discussed.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="symptom-item">
              <div class="symptom-icon">😴</div>
              <div class="symptom-text">
                <div class="symptom-name">Sleep disruption (for some)</div>
                <div class="symptom-reason">Some women's sleep improves; for others it persists, especially without progesterone support</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="symptom-item">
              <div class="symptom-icon">🧠</div>
              <div class="symptom-text">
                <div class="symptom-name">Brain fog &amp; memory concerns</div>
                <div class="symptom-reason">Oestrogen supports cognitive function — low stable oestrogen can still affect memory and focus without treatment</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="symptom-item">
              <div class="symptom-icon">🦴</div>
              <div class="symptom-text">
                <div class="symptom-name">Joint pain &amp; bone loss</div>
                <div class="symptom-reason">Bone density loss accelerates most in the first 5–7 years after menopause — joint pain can persist or worsen</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="symptom-item">
              <div class="symptom-icon">❤️</div>
              <div class="symptom-text">
                <div class="symptom-name">Cardiovascular &amp; metabolic risk</div>
                <div class="symptom-reason">These are silent — no symptoms until there are. This is why long-term health management matters from the point of menopause</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="ig-callout ig-callout--peach" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <span class="ig-callout-icon">💡</span>
        <span>Menopause is not the end of symptoms — it is a transition point. Many symptoms that persist respond well to HRT started at or around menopause. It is never too late to ask. <a href="/blog/hormonal-symptom-treatments-perimenopause" class="ig-callout-link">See treatment options →</a></span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 04 — INDIA PICTURE -->
  <section class="ig-section bg-cream">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ig-card-label center">04 / The Indian Context</div>
      <h2 class="ig-section-title center">What menopause means for Indian women specifically</h2>
      <p class="ig-section-sub center">The biology, the culture, and the healthcare system create a specific picture for Indian women — one that Western guidelines often miss.</p>

      <div class="india-grid">
        {[
          {
            icon: '📆',
            title: 'Earlier onset, longer postmenopause',
            desc: 'Menopause at 46–47 means Indian women live in postmenopause for 35+ years on average. That is a long time — long-term bone and heart protection is not optional — and emerging evidence suggests possible cognitive benefit from HRT, though this is still being studied. It is essential.'
          },
          {
            icon: '🦴',
            title: 'Higher bone risk',
            desc: 'Indian women have lower peak bone mass than Western women — a well-documented difference. Combined with earlier menopause, osteoporosis risk is significant, serious, and dramatically under-diagnosed.'
          },
          {
            icon: '🔇',
            title: 'The language gap',
            desc: 'There is no specific word for menopause in most Indian languages. The entire experience — the symptoms, the transition, the health needs — is effectively invisible in conversation, in families, and often in clinics.'
          },
          {
            icon: '💊',
            title: 'HRT access and stigma',
            desc: 'Body-identical HRT is available in India and is appropriate for the vast majority of women. Persistent myths about cancer risk — based on outdated research — keep many women from accessing treatments that could protect their long-term health.'
          },
        ].map(item => (
          <div class="india-card">
            <div class="india-icon">{item.icon}</div>
            <h3 class="india-title">{item.title}</h3>
            <p class="india-desc">{item.desc}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 05 — WHAT HELPS -->
  <section class="ig-section bg-white">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ig-card-label center">05 / Protecting Your Health</div>
      <h2 class="ig-section-title center">How to protect your health in postmenopause</h2>
      <p class="ig-section-sub center">Postmenopause is not a passive phase. The choices made in the years around menopause shape long-term health for decades.</p>

      <div class="helps-grid">
        <div class="helps-col">
          <div class="helps-head helps-head--medical">🩺 Medical</div>
          <ul class="helps-list">
            <li><strong>HRT</strong> — protects bones and heart — and emerging evidence suggests possible cognitive benefit, though this is still being studied. Relieves symptoms. Most effective when started within 10 years of menopause.</li>
            <li><strong>Vaginal oestrogen</strong> — local, safe, and highly effective for GSM. Does not carry the same considerations as systemic HRT.</li>
            <li><strong>DEXA scan</strong> — bone density assessment. Ask your gynaecologist about timing and frequency.</li>
            <li><strong>Regular blood pressure monitoring</strong> — cardiovascular risk rises postmenopause. Know your numbers.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="helps-col">
          <div class="helps-head helps-head--lifestyle">🌿 Lifestyle</div>
          <ul class="helps-list">
            <li><strong>Strength training</strong> — the single most important exercise for bone density and muscle mass. Twice a week minimum.</li>
            <li><strong>Calcium + Vitamin D</strong> — essential for bone health. Most Indian women are deficient. Test and supplement.</li>
            <li><strong>Protein at every meal</strong> — preserves muscle mass that is harder to build postmenopause.</li>
            <li><strong>Reduce alcohol and smoking</strong> — both accelerate bone loss and cardiovascular risk significantly.</li>
            <li><strong>Phytoestrogens</strong> — til, flaxseed, soy, lentils, and rajma offer mild oestrogen-like benefit.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="helps-col">
          <div class="helps-head helps-head--support">🧪 Tests to ask for</div>
          <ul class="helps-list">
            <li><strong>Bone density (DEXA)</strong> — at or around menopause, especially if Indian, slim, or with family history</li>
            <li><strong>Lipid panel</strong> — cardiovascular risk rises postmenopause</li>
            <li><strong>Fasting glucose and HbA1c</strong> — metabolic changes continue</li>
            <li><strong>Blood pressure</strong> — monitor regularly</li>
            <li><strong>Thyroid (TSH)</strong> — thyroid issues are common and overlap with menopause symptoms</li>
            <li><strong>Vitamin D, B12, ferritin</strong> — deficiencies worsen every symptom; extremely common in Indian women</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="ig-cta-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ig-cta-inner">
        <div class="ig-cta-left">
          <h2>Still in perimenopause? Our free symptom check can tell you where you are in your transition.</h2>
          <p>Built specifically for Indian women. No login, no jargon, no judgement — just clarity about where you are and what your options look like.</p>
          <div class="ig-cta-btns">
            <a href="/quiz" class="btn btn-peach btn-lg">Check My Symptoms →</a>
            <a href="/chat" class="btn btn-outline-white">Talk Privately</a>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ig-cta-stat-col">
          <div class="ig-stat"><span class="ig-stat-num">46–47</span><span class="ig-stat-label">Average age of menopause for Indian women — 4–5 years earlier than the West</span></div>
          <div class="ig-stat"><span class="ig-stat-num">35+</span><span class="ig-stat-label">Years the average Indian woman lives in postmenopause</span></div>
          <div class="ig-stat"><span class="ig-stat-num">10 yr</span><span class="ig-stat-label">Window of greatest HRT benefit for bones and heart — with emerging evidence for cognitive benefit</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>

<style>
  /* HERO */
  .ig-hero {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0F2A1A 0%, #1A3D2B 60%, #2A5C45 100%);
    color: #fff;
    padding: 6rem 0 5rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .ig-hero-inner { max-width: 680px; margin: 0 auto; }
  .ig-eyebrow { display: inline-block; background: rgba(255,255,255,.12); border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.2); color: rgba(255,255,255,.85); font-size: .78rem; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: .1em; text-transform: uppercase; padding: .4rem 1rem; border-radius: 100px; margin-bottom: 1.25rem; }
  .ig-hero h1 { font-size: clamp(2.2rem, 5vw, 3.4rem); font-weight: 900; letter-spacing: -.03em; color: #fff; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .ig-hero p { font-size: 1.1rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,.75); margin-bottom: 2rem; }
  .ig-share-row { display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; gap: 1rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .ig-share-label { font-size: .85rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,.55); }
  .ig-share-btn { font-size: .82rem; font-weight: 700; padding: .45rem 1rem; border-radius: 99px; text-decoration: none; }
  .ig-wa { background: #25D366; color: #fff; }

  /* SECTIONS */
  .ig-section { padding: 5rem 0; }
  .bg-white { background: #fff; }
  .bg-cream { background: var(--cream, #F9F5F0); }
  .ig-card-label { font-size: .72rem; font-weight: 800; letter-spacing: .12em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--green, #1A3D2B); background: var(--green-light, #E8F0EB); display: inline-block; padding: .3rem .9rem; border-radius: 99px; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .ig-card-label.center { display: block; text-align: center; }
  .ig-section-title { font-size: clamp(1.6rem, 3vw, 2.2rem); font-weight: 900; letter-spacing: -.025em; color: var(--text, #1a1a1a); margin-bottom: .75rem; text-align: center; }
  .ig-section-sub { font-size: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary, #555); line-height: 1.7; text-align: center; max-width: 600px; margin: 0 auto 3rem; }
  .ig-card--full { background: var(--cream, #F9F5F0); border-radius: 20px; padding: 2.5rem; }
  .ig-card-title { font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 2.5vw, 2rem); font-weight: 900; color: var(--text, #1a1a1a); letter-spacing: -.02em; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
  .ig-card-title em { font-style: normal; color: var(--green, #1A3D2B); }

  /* DEFINITION INTRO */
  .def-intro { margin-bottom: 2rem; }
  .def-intro p { font-size: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary, #555); line-height: 1.7; }

  /* DEFINITION BLOCKS */
  .def-blocks { display: flex; align-items: stretch; gap: 0; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .def-block { flex: 1; background: #fff; border-radius: 16px; padding: 1.5rem; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: .5rem; }
  .def-block--peri { border: 2px solid #D4845A; }
  .def-block--meno { border: 2px solid var(--green, #1A3D2B); background: linear-gradient(135deg, #E8F0EB, #C8DDD0); }
  .def-block--post { border: 2px solid #7FB89A; }
  .def-arrow { display: flex; align-items: center; padding: 0 1rem; font-size: 1.5rem; color: var(--text-muted, #aaa); flex-shrink: 0; }
  .def-block-icon { font-size: 1.8rem; }
  .def-block-label { font-size: .9rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: .06em; color: var(--text, #1a1a1a); }
  .def-block--meno .def-block-label { color: var(--green, #1A3D2B); }
  .def-block-desc { font-size: .85rem; color: var(--text-secondary, #555); line-height: 1.65; }
  .def-link { color: var(--green, #1A3D2B); font-weight: 700; text-decoration: none; }
  .def-link:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

  /* TIMELINE */
  .timeline-wrap { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0; max-width: 640px; }
  .tl-item { display: flex; gap: 1.5rem; align-items: flex-start; padding-bottom: .5rem; }
  .tl-line { width: 2px; background: var(--border, #e0e0e0); height: 2rem; margin-left: 11px; }
  .tl-dot { width: 24px; height: 24px; border-radius: 50%; flex-shrink: 0; margin-top: .2rem; }
  .tl-dot--green { background: var(--green, #1A3D2B); }
  .tl-dot--peach { background: #D4845A; box-shadow: 0 0 0 6px rgba(212,132,90,.2); }
  .tl-dot--pulse { animation: pulse 2s infinite; }
  @keyframes pulse { 0%,100% { box-shadow: 0 0 0 4px rgba(212,132,90,.2); } 50% { box-shadow: 0 0 0 10px rgba(212,132,90,.08); } }
  .tl-dot--muted { background: var(--border, #ccc); }
  .tl-dot--light { background: #ddd; }
  .tl-age { font-size: .75rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-muted, #888); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: .06em; margin-bottom: .2rem; }
  .tl-label { font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--text, #1a1a1a); margin-bottom: .3rem; }
  .tl-label--highlight { color: #D4845A; }
  .tl-desc { font-size: .88rem; color: var(--text-secondary, #555); line-height: 1.6; }
  .tl-desc em { font-style: italic; color: var(--text, #1a1a1a); }

  /* CALLOUT */
  .ig-callout { display: flex; gap: 1rem; align-items: flex-start; background: var(--green-light, #E8F0EB); border-left: 4px solid var(--green, #1A3D2B); border-radius: 0 12px 12px 0; padding: 1.1rem 1.25rem; margin-top: 2rem; font-size: .9rem; color: var(--text, #1a1a1a); line-height: 1.65; }
